{\pard\sb360\sa360\fs48 The Fidelity of the Rechabites contrasted with the Disobedience of the Jews
 
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\cf1 35}In the days of Jehoiakim, the son of Josiah, king of{\super\cf2\fs24 1}Judah, Jeremiah received the following message from {\super\cf2\fs24 2}Jehovah: Go to the clan of the Rechabites, talk withthem, bring them into one of the chambers (of the {\super\cf2\fs24 3}Temple) and offer them wine to drink. So I tookJaazaniah, the son of Jeremiah, the son of Habaz-ziniah, with his brothers and all his sons and the whole {\super\cf2\fs24 4}Rechabite clan, and brought them into the Templechamber belonging to the sons of Hanan, the son ofYigdaliah, the man of God, that was adjacent to thechamber of the princes, above the chamber ofMaaseiah, the son of Shallum, the Keeper of the {\super\cf2\fs24 5}Threshold. I then set before the Rechabites bowls {\super\cf2\fs24 6}full of wine and cups and told them to drink. "No,"they said, "we will drink no wine; for Jonadab, theson of Rechab, our ancestor, laid a charge upon us and {\super\cf2\fs24 7}our children to drink no wine, to build no houses, to sowno seed, to plant and possess no vineyard for ever, but tospend all our days in tents, so that we might live long on {\super\cf2\fs24 8}the land where as strangers we dwell. In full obedience,therefore, to this charge of Jonadab, the son of Rechab,our ancestor, we have drunk no wine all our life long,neither we, nor our wives, nor our sons, nor our {\super\cf2\fs24 9}daughters. We have built no houses to live in, we {\super\cf2\fs24 10}have owned neither vineyard, field, nor seed, butwe have lived in tents and faithfully fulfilled all the {\super\cf2\fs24 11}instructions of our ancestors Jonadab. It was onlywhen the land was invaded by Nebuchadrezzar, kingof Babylon, that we decided to come to Jerusalem, toescape the Babylonian and Aramean armies; that iswhy we are (now) living in Jerusalem."
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 12}Then there came to Jeremiah this message from {\super\cf2\fs24 13}Jehovah: "Thus saith Jehovah the God of Israel:Go and say to the men of Judah and the citizens ofJerusalem: Should this not be a lesson to you to obey {\super\cf2\fs24 14}My words, saith Jehovah? The injunction thatJonadab the son of Rechab laid upon his sons todrink no wine has been steadily observed: in obedienceto that ancestral charge they have abstained to this day.But when I spoke to you early and late, you refused {\super\cf2\fs24 15}to listen. Early and late I sent you all My servants theprophets with the message to each man of you that, ifyou would abandon your wicked ways, amend yourconduct, and no longer indulge in the service of othergods, you should continue in the land that I gave yourforefathers; but you would not incline your ear or {\super\cf2\fs24 16}listen to Me. Unlike the descendants of Jonadab theson of Rechab, who have steadily observed the in-junctions of their ancestor, this people has refused to {\super\cf2\fs24 17}listen to Me. Therefore thus saith Jehovah of Hosts,the God of Israel: See! I am about to bring uponJudah and upon all the citizens of Jerusalem all themisery with which I have threatened them, becausethey refused to listen to My words or respond to My {\super\cf2\fs24 18}call." But to the clan of the Rechabites Jeremiah said,"Thus saith Jehovah of Hosts, the God of Israel:Because you have obeyed the injunction of yourancestor Jonadab, keeping all his commandments and {\super\cf2\fs24 19}fulfiling all his instructions, Jonadab, the son of Rechabshall never want a man to minister to Me, while theearth stands.
\par}

{\pard\sb360\sa360\fs48 Jeremiah\uc1\u8217*s Prophecies Committed to Writing, Publicly Read in the Temple,
and Contemptuously Burned by King Jehoiakim 
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\cf1 36}In the fourth year of Jehoiakim, the son of Josiah,{\super\cf2\fs24 1}king of Judah, Jeremiah received the following message {\super\cf2\fs24 2}from Jehovah: Take a book-roll, and write on it allthe messages I have communicated to thee with regardto Israel and Judah and all nations, from My firstmessage to thee in the days of Josiah right on to the {\super\cf2\fs24 3}present day. It may be that, when the people ofJudah hear of all the misery I am planning to bringupon them, they will severally abandon their wickedways, and receive at My hands pardon for their guiltand sin.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 4}Then Jeremiah summoned Baruch, the son of Neriah,who wrote down on a book-roll to Jeremiah\uc1\u8217*s dic-tation all the messages Jehovah had communicated to {\super\cf2\fs24 5}him. Thereafter Jeremiah gave instructions toBaruch in the following terms: "Seeing that I ampersonally under restraint and debarred from access {\super\cf2\fs24 6}to the Temple, do you go and, on the day appointedfor fasting, read aloud in the Temple the messages ofJehovah in the hearing of the people from the rollwhich you have written to my dictation; read themalso in the hearing of the Judeans who come from their {\super\cf2\fs24 7}respective country towns. It may be that they willhumbly supplicate Jehovah, and severally abandontheir wicked ways: for great is the anger and fury {\super\cf2\fs24 8}with which Jehovah has threatened this people." Inaccordance, therefore with his instructions fromJeremiah the prophet, Baruch read aloud from thebook the words of Jehovah in the Temple.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 9}Now in the ninth month of the fifth year of Jehoiakimthe son of Josiah, king of Judah, a sacred fast wasproclaimed by all the people resident in Jerusalem,and all those also present from the country towns of {\super\cf2\fs24 10}Judah. Then in the hearing of all the people Baruchread from the book the messages of Jeremiah from theroom that belonged to Gemariah, the son of Shaphanthe Secretary of State, which was situated in the upper {\super\cf2\fs24 11}court at the entrance to the new Temple gate. Nowwhen Micaiah, the son of Gemariah, the son ofShaphan, had heard the messages of Jehovah as they {\super\cf2\fs24 12}were read from the book, he went down to the palaceto the room of the Secretary of State, and there he foundthe whole court seated \uc1\u8211* Elishama, the Secretary andDelaiah, the son of Shemaiah, and Elanthan, theson of Achbor, and Gemariah, the son of Shaphan, andZedekiah, the son of Hananiah, and indeed the whole {\super\cf2\fs24 13}court. Micaiah proceeded to inform them of all thewords he had heard Baruch read out of the book in the {\super\cf2\fs24 14}hearing of the people. The whole court accordinglydespatched a messenger to Baruch, namely one Jehudi,the son of Nethaniah, the son of Shelemiah, the son ofCushi, with instructions to Baruch to appear, bring-ing with him the roll from which he had read in thehearing of the people. So Baruch, the son of Neriah,appeared before them with the roll in his hand.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 15}Then they told him to sit down and read it in their {\super\cf2\fs24 16}hearing; so Baruch read while they listened. Whenthey had heard it all, they turned to one another inconsternation, exclaiming to Baruch that they were {\super\cf2\fs24 17}bound to inform the king of all this. They thenasked Baruch to explain how he had written all these {\super\cf2\fs24 18}words. Baruch replied that Jeremiah had dictatedthem all to him, and he had written them down with {\super\cf2\fs24 19}ink in the book. "Well, then," said the princes toBaruch, "go into hiding, you and Jeremiah, and let {\super\cf2\fs24 20}nobody know where you are." After they haddeposited the roll in the chamber of Elishama theSecretary, they visited the king in his apartment,and reported the whole matter to him.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 21}The king then despatched Jehudi to fetch the roll;and, when he had brought it form Elishama\uc1\u8217*s chamber,he read it in the hearing of the king and of all the {\super\cf2\fs24 22}courtiers who were in attendance upon him. Nowthe king was sitting in the winter house, and the {\super\cf2\fs24 23}fire on the brazier was burning before him; andevery three or four columns that Jehudi read, the kingwould cut up with his penknife and fling into the firethat was on the brazier, till the whole roll was con- {\super\cf2\fs24 24}sumed in the fire that was on the brazier. But therewas no sense of horror either on the part of the kingor of any of his ministers as they listened to all these {\super\cf2\fs24 25}words, nor did they rend their garments. Elnathan,Delaiah, and Gemariah, however, had entreated theking not to burn the roll, but he would not listen to {\super\cf2\fs24 26}them. Then the king commanded the royal princeJerachmeel, and seraiah, the son of Azriel, andShelemiah, the son of Abdeel, to fetch Baruch the scribeand Jeremiah the prophet; but Jehovah kept them inconcealment.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 27}After the king had burned the roll containing thewords written by Baruch to Jeremiah\uc1\u8217*s dictation, {\super\cf2\fs24 28}Jeremiah received this message from Jehovah, "Oncemore take another roll, and write on it all the wordsthat were on the first roll that was consigned to the {\super\cf2\fs24 29}flames by Jehoiakim, king of Judah, Thus saithJehovah: Thou hast taken it upon thee to burn thisroll and to demand my reason for recording the threatthat the king of Babylon would assuredly come and {\super\cf2\fs24 30}destroy this land, and clear it of man and beast. There-fore thus saith Jehovah concerning Jehoiakim, king ofJudah: Never a man shall he have to sit upon thethrone of David; his dead body shall be flung out and {\super\cf2\fs24 31}exposed to the heat of day and the cold of night. Iwill punish him, his descendants, and his ministers, fortheir sins; and I will bring upon them and upon thecitizens of Jerusalem all the misery with which Ithreatened them in vain."
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 32}Then Jeremiah took another roll and gave it toBaruch the scribe, the son of Neriah, who wrote on itto Jeremiah\uc1\u8217*s dictation all the words of the book thathad been burned by Jehoiakim; and it was supple-mented by many messages of a similar kind.
\par}

{\pard\sb360\sa360\fs36 Experiences of Jeremiah During the Siege and at the Capture of Jerusalem

\par}

{\pard\sb360\sa360\fs48 Jeremiah Warns King Zedekiah of the Impending Fate of Jerusalem
 
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\cf1 37}Now Zedekiah the son of Josiah was reigning in place{\super\cf2\fs24 1}of Coniah, the son of Jehoiakim, having been set uponthe throne of Judah by Nebuchadrezzar, king of Baby- {\super\cf2\fs24 2}lon; but neither he nor his ministers nor the peopleof the land gave any heed to the messages Jehovah {\super\cf2\fs24 3}had delivered by the prophet Jeremiah. KingZedekiah, however, sent Jehucal the son of Shelemiah,and Zephaniah the son of Maaseiah the priest toJeremiah, with the request that he would pray for {\super\cf2\fs24 4}them to Jehovah their God. Now Jeremiah, who hadnot yet been put in prison, was still coming andgoing among the people.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 5}The Chaledeans who were engaged in the siege ofJerusalem, having received a report that Pharaoh\uc1\u8217*sarmy was advancing from Egypt, abandoned the siege. {\super\cf2\fs24 6}Then there came to Jeremiah this message from {\super\cf2\fs24 7}Jehovah, Thus saith Jehovah: Tell the king ofJudah who hath sent thee to consult Me, thatPharaoh\uc1\u8217*s army which is advancing to your aid {\super\cf2\fs24 8}shall return to Egypt to their own land; and theChaldeans will come back and assault this city {\super\cf2\fs24 9}and take it and burn it with fire. Thus saith Jehovah:Do not delude yourselves with the idea that the Chal-deans will leave you for good: they will do nothing of {\super\cf2\fs24 10}the kind. For even if you defeated the wholeChaldean army that is fighting against you, so com-pletely that the only survivors were wounded men \uc1\u8211* aman to a tent\uc1\u8211* even they would rise up and burn thiscity with fire.
\par}

{\pard\sb360\sa360\fs48 Jeremiah Arrested and Imprisoned

\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 11}When, in view of the advance of Pharoah\uc1\u8217*s army,the Chaldean forces had abandoned the siege of {\super\cf2\fs24 12}Jerusalem, Jeremiah made a journey from Jerusalemto the district of Benjamin to receive his inheritance {\super\cf2\fs24 13}among the people. He had just reached the Benjamingate when he was apprehended there by a sentrynamed Jirijah, the son of Shelemiah, the son ofHananiah, who called out, "You are deserting to the {\super\cf2\fs24 14}Chaldeans." "It is false, said Jeremiah, "I amnot deserting to the Chaldeans." But Jirijah, refusingto listen, apprehended Jeremiah and brought him {\super\cf2\fs24 15}before the courtiers, who in their exasperation hadJeremiah flogged and put in the house of Jonathan,the Secretary of State, which they had turned into a {\super\cf2\fs24 16}prison. So Jeremiah found himself in the cells of thedungeon, where he remained for a considerable time.
\par}

{\pard\sb360\sa360\fs48 Amelioration of Jeremiah\uc1\u8217*s Lot

\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 17}Then King Zedekiah sent for him and questionedhim secretly in his house whether there was any com-munication from Jehovah. "There is," said Jeremiah;"you will be delivered into the hands of the king of {\super\cf2\fs24 18}Babylon. Further," said Jeremiah to the king,"what is my crime against you or your ministers or {\super\cf2\fs24 19}this people that you have put me in prison? Whereare your prophets (now) that assured you that the king {\super\cf2\fs24 20}of Babylon would never invade this country? Andnow I beseech your Majesty to listen with favour to mysupplication, and not to allow me to be taken backto the house of Jonathan the Secretary, where I am {\super\cf2\fs24 21}likely to perish." Jeremiah was accordingly committedby royal command to the guard-court, and furnishedwith a loaf of bread a day from the Baker\uc1\u8217*s Street, tillall the bread in the city was consumed. So Jeremiahremained in the guard-court.
\par}

{\pard\sb360\sa360\fs48 Jeremiah Accused of Treason, is Put into a Dungeon, from which he is
Rescued by Ebedmelech, a Foreigner 
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\cf1 38}Now Shephatiah, the son of Mattan, and Gedaliah, the{\super\cf2\fs24 1}son of Pashhur, and Juca, the son of Shelemiah, andPashhur, the son of Malchiah, ahd heard Jeremiah {\super\cf2\fs24 2}addressing all the people in words like these: "Thussaith Jehovah: Whoever remains in this city shall dieby sword, famine and perstilence; but whoever goesover to the Chaldeans shall be spared, though he shall {\super\cf2\fs24 3}escape with nothing but his life." Also, "Thus saithJehovah, This city shall most assuredly be deliveredinto the hands of the king of Babylon\uc1\u8217*s army, and {\super\cf2\fs24 4}it shall be captured." Whereupon those courtierssaid to the king, "We petition you to have this fellowput to death: this sort of talk is unnerving all thepeople and the soldiers left in the city. This fellow {\super\cf2\fs24 5}does not want to help the city, but to ruin it." "Heis in your power," said the king; for he was helpless {\super\cf2\fs24 6}against them. So they took Jeremiah and, loweringhim with ropes, they threw him into the cistern of theroyal prince Malchiah, that was in the guard-court.There was no water in the cistern, but only mud;and Jeremiah sank in the mud.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 7}Now it came to the ears of Ebedmelech, an Ethiopianeunuch attached to the palace, that they had put {\super\cf2\fs24 8}Jeremiah in the cistern. Ebedmelech accordingly leftthe palace for the Benjamin gate where the kinghappened to be sitting at the time, and thus he {\super\cf2\fs24 9}addressed him: "Your Majesty, these men havebehaved most wrongfully in their treatment of Jeremiahthe prophet; they have flung him into the cistern andhe will die of hunger on the spot, for there is no more {\super\cf2\fs24 10}bread in the city." At once the king orderedEbedmelech to take with him three me and pullJeremiah out of the cistern before he perished. {\super\cf2\fs24 11}Ebedmelech, accordingly, taking the men with him,went to the palace, and secured form (a lumber room)underneath the treasury some torn and tattered rags,and let them down by ropes to Jeremiah into the {\super\cf2\fs24 12}cistern. Then he told Jeremiah to put the torn andtattered rags under his armpits beneath the ropes; {\super\cf2\fs24 13}and Jeremiah did so. Then they drew him up with theropes and pulled him out of the cistern; and Jeremiahremained in the guard-court.
\par}

{\pard\sb360\sa360\fs48 Zedekiah Secretly Consults Jeremiah

\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 14}King Zedekiah afterwards sent and had Jeremiahbrought to him at the third entry that leads into theTemple; and the king said to Jeremiah, "I am goingto ask you a question which you are to answer me {\super\cf2\fs24 15}unreservedly." "If I tell you," said Jeremiah, "areyou not certain to put me to death? besides, any advice {\super\cf2\fs24 16}I give you, you will simply disregard." Then, in secret,the king swore the following oath to Jeremiah, "AsJehovah liveth, who created this life of ours, I assureyou solemnly that I will neither put you to death nordeliver you into the hands of those men that are seek- {\super\cf2\fs24 17}ing your life." Then said Jeremiah to Zedekiah,"Thus saith Jehovah, If you surrender voluntarily tothe officers of the king of Babylon, your life will bespared, and this city shall not be burned with fire, but {\super\cf2\fs24 18}you and your family will be spared. If, however, yourefuse to surrender, then this city shall be deliveredinto the handso of the Chaldeans, who will burn it withfire; and you shall not escape from their hands." {\super\cf2\fs24 19}Then the king said to Jeremiah, "I am afraid of theJews who have gone over to them and subjected to violence." {\super\cf2\fs24 20}"No," said Jeremiah, "you will not be handed over.But I entreat you to listen to what I say \uc1\u8211* it is thevoice of Jehovah: your happiness and your life depend {\super\cf2\fs24 21}upon it. But if you refuse to surrender, then this isthe message revealed to me in a vision by Jehovah {\super\cf2\fs24 22}\uc1\u8211*mark it well; (I saw) all the women that are left inthe palace of the king of Judah brought out to the chiefofficers of the king of Babylon, chanting the while thissong:
\par}

{\pard\fi-2440\li2800
Thy most excellent friends have beguiled
\par}

{\pard\fi-2080\li2800
And prevailed over thee,
\par}

{\pard\fi-2440\li2800
Thy feet they have thrust in the mire,
\par}

{\pard\fi-2080\li2800
And thus sinking have left thee.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 23}All your wives and children they shall bring out tothe Chaldeans, and you yourself shall not escape; youwill be seized by the hand of the king of Babylon; andthis city shall be burned with fire."
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 24}"Well, then," said the king to him, "let nobodyknow anything of this conversation, or else you are a dead {\super\cf2\fs24 25}man. If the courtiers hear that I have been talkingwith you, and come and ask you to tell them un-reservedly, on pain of death, what you have been saying {\super\cf2\fs24 26}to the king and the king to you, then just tell them thatyou were presenting a petition to the king that youshould not be taken back to Jonathan\uc1\u8217*s house, where {\super\cf2\fs24 27}you were in danger of perishing." In point of fact, thecourtiers did all come to Jeremiah and question him;and the story he told them was in entire accordancewith the king\uc1\u8217*s instructions. So they said no more tohim, for no part of the conversation had been heard. {\super\cf2\fs24 28a}Jeremiah accordingly remained in the guard-courttill the day Jerusalem was taken.
\par}

{\pard\sb360\sa360\fs48 Provision made for Jeremiah\uc1\u8217*s safety after the Capture of Jerusalem

\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 28b}When Jerusalem was taken, all the chief officers of  {\cf1 39}the king of Babylon came and took their seats{\super\cf2\fs24 3}in the middle gate \uc1\u8211* Nergalsharezer the Rab-mag,Nebushazban the Rab-saris, and all the rest of the {\super\cf2\fs24 14}Officers of the king of Babylon. They sent and hadJeremiah brought from the guard-court, and deliveredhim to Gedaliah, the son of Ahikam, the son ofShaphan, to be taken to his own home; so he stayedamong the people.
\par}

{\pard\sb360\sa360\fs48 The Capture of Jerusalem

\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 1}In the tenth month of the ninth year of Zedekiah,king of Judah, Nebuchadrezzar, king of Babylon camewith all his forces against Jerusalem and laid siege to {\super\cf2\fs24 2}it. On the ninth day of the fourth month of theeleventh year of Zedekiah a breach was made in the {\super\cf2\fs24 4}city. On observing this, Zedekiah, king of Judah, andall the soldiers took to flight, leaving the city during thenight by way of the royal garden, by the gate betweenthe two walls, and they made for the Jordan valley. {\super\cf2\fs24 5}But the Chaldean army pursued them and overtookZedekiah in the steppes of Jericho. They seized himand brought him to Nebuchadrezzar king of Babylon,who was at Riblah in the district of Hamath, and he {\super\cf2\fs24 6}pronounced judgment upon them. At Riblah theking of Babylon slew the sons of Zedekiah before hiseyes, and all the noblemen of Judah also did the king {\super\cf2\fs24 7}of Babylon slay. He then put out Zedekiah\uc1\u8217*s eyes,and loaded him with chains to carry him to Babylon. {\super\cf2\fs24 8}The palace and the houses of the people the Chaldeansburned with fire, and the walls of Jerusalem they {\super\cf2\fs24 9}demolished. The rest of the people that were left in thecity, and the deserters who had gonve over to him, andthose that werer left of the artificers, Nebuzaradan, thecommander of the guard, carried to exile in Babylon. {\super\cf2\fs24 10}Some of the poor people who had nothing were left byNebuzaradan, the commander of the guard, in the landof Judah, and presented at the same time with vine-yards and fields.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 11}With regard to Jeremiah, Nebuchadrezzar, king ofBabylon, had instructed Nebuzardan, the commander {\super\cf2\fs24 12}of the guard, to do him no harm, but to take and lookwell afer him and treat him according to his own {\super\cf2\fs24 13}instructions. So a messenger was despatched fromNebuzaradan, the commander of the guard, andNebuzaradan, the Rab-saris, and Nergalsharezer, theRab-mag, and all the chief officers of the king ofBabylon.
\par}

{\pard\sb360\sa360\fs48 Jeremiah\uc1\u8217*s Gracious Promise to Ebedmelech

\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 15}During Jeremiah\uc1\u8217*s detention in the guard-court,there had come to him this message from Jehovah: {\super\cf2\fs24 16}Go and say to Ebedmelech the Ethiopian, Thus saithJehovah of Hosts, the God of Israel: I will bring uponthis city all that I have said \uc1\u8211* for evil and not for good,and in that day it will be accomplished before thine {\super\cf2\fs24 17}eyes. But, saith Jehovah, I will deliver thee on thatday, and thou shalt not be given into the hands of the {\super\cf2\fs24 18}men thou dreadest. I will save thee without fail;thou shalt not fall by the sword, but thou shalt escapewith thy life, because, saith Jehovah, thou hast putthy trust in Me.
\par}

{\pard\sb360\sa360\fs36 Experiences of Jeremiah After the Capture of Jerusalem

\par}

{\pard\sb360\sa360\fs48 Jeremiah Elects to Remain in Palestine
 
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\cf1 40}The message which came to Jeremiah from Jehovah{\super\cf2\fs24 1}after he had been released from Ramah by Nebuzar-adan, the commander of the guard, who had found himthere in chains among the captives of Jerusalem andJudah, who were being carried to exile in Babylon.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 2}The commander of the guard took Jeremiah and saidto him: "Jehovah, your God, pronounced this doom {\super\cf2\fs24 3}upon this place, and He has kept His word. Youhave sinned against Him and refused to listen to His {\super\cf2\fs24 4}voice, and so this thing is come upon you. But see now,I will release you at once from the chains on your hands.If you are disposed to accompany me to Babyloncome and I will look well after you; but if not, thenleave it alone. The whole land is before you; go {\super\cf2\fs24 5}wherever you choose and prefer. Go back to Gedaliah,the son of Ahikam, the son of Shaphan, whom the kingof Babylon has appointed Governor of the cities ofJudah: stay with him among the people or go whereveryou choose." Then the commander of the guarddismissed him with a gift of provisions and a present. {\super\cf2\fs24 6}So Jeremiah went to Gedaliah at Mizpah, where hestayed with him among the people left in the land.
\par}

{\pard\sb360\sa360\fs48 Assassination of Gedaliah the Governor of Judah

\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 7}When all the commanders of the forces in the openfield, together with their men, heard that the king ofBabylon had appointed Gedaliah Governor of the land,and charged him with the oversight of the men, womenand children, and of the poorest of the land, such as {\super\cf2\fs24 8}had not been carried to exile in Babylon, they camewith their men to Gedaliah at Mizpah \uc1\u8211* Ishmael theson of Nethaniah, Johanan and Jonathan the sons ofKareah, Seraiah the son of Tanhumeth, and the sons ofEphai of Netophah, and Jezaniah, the son of the {\super\cf2\fs24 9}Maacathite. And Gedaliah gave his oath to them andtheir men: "Don\uc1\u8217*t be afraid," he said, "of theChaldean officials. You will prosper if you stay in the {\super\cf2\fs24 10}land and serve the king of Babylon. As for myself,I will reside at Mizpah, to represent your interestswhen the Chaldean (officials) visit us; and you cangather wine, fruit, and oil, and store them up and live {\super\cf2\fs24 11}in the towns you take possession of." Further, all theJews that were in Moab, Ammon, Edom, or elsewhere,when they heard that the king of Babylon had grantedpermission to some to remain in Judah and had ap- {\super\cf2\fs24 12}pointed Gedaliah the son of Ahikam Governor, theyall returned to Judah from all the places to which theyhad been driven \uc1\u8211* to Gedaliah at Mizpah \uc1\u8211* and theygathered immense stores of wine and fruit.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 13}Now Johanan the son of Kareah and all the com-manders of the forces in the open field came to Gedaliah {\super\cf2\fs24 14}at Mizpah, and asked him whether he was awarethat Baalis king of Ammon had sent Ishmael the son ofNethaniah to assasiante him. But Gedaliah would {\super\cf2\fs24 15}not believe it. Then Johanan, in a secret audience withGedaliah at Mizpah, said to him: "I beseech you toallow me to go and slay Ishmael. Nobody need know.Why should he take your life? that will mean thescattering of all the Jews that have gathered round {\super\cf2\fs24 16}you, and the ruin of all that is left of Judah." "No,"said Gedaliah to Johanan, "do nothing of the kind:what you say of Ishmael is not true." 
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\cf1 41}In the seventh month, however, Ishamael, the son{\super\cf2\fs24 1}of Nethaniah, the son of Elishama, a member of theroyal family, accompanied by one of the chief officers ofthe king and ten (other) men, paid a visit to Gedaliah {\super\cf2\fs24 2}at Mizpah. While they were all dining together there,Ishmael and the ten men who accompanied him roseand with the sword smote and slew Gedaliah, whom theking of Babylon had appointed Governor of the land, {\super\cf2\fs24 3}together with all the Jews who were with him inMizpah and all the Chaldean soldiers who happenedto be there.
\par}

{\pard\sb360\sa360\fs48 Murder of Pilgrims and Flight of Gedaliah\uc1\u8217*s Assasin

\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
