{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 4}On the tenth day of the tenth month of the ninthyear of his reign Nebuchadrezzar, king of Babylon,came with all his forces to storm Jerusalem. Theypitched their camp against it, and surrounded it with {\super\cf2\fs24 5}a siege-wall; so the city was undersiege till the eleventh {\super\cf2\fs24 6}year of king Zedekiah. In the ninth day of the fourthmonth \uc1\u8211* the famine in the city being so severe that {\super\cf2\fs24 7}there was no bread for the people of the land \uc1\u8211* abreach was made in the city, and all the soldiers tookto flight, leaving the city during the night by way of thegate between the two walls by the royal garden\uc1\u8211*the city being surrounded by the Chaldeans \uc1\u8211* and they {\super\cf2\fs24 8}made for the Jordan valley. But the Chaldean armypursued the king and overtook him in the steppes ofJericho, all his own army having left him and scattered. {\super\cf2\fs24 9}They seized the king and brought him to the king ofBabylon who was at Riblah in the district of Hamath; {\super\cf2\fs24 10}and he pronounced judgment upon him. At Riblahthe king of Babylon slew the sons of Zedekiah beforehis eyes, and all the princes of Judah did he also slay; {\super\cf2\fs24 11}he then put out Zedekiah\uc1\u8217*s eyes, and having loaded himwith chains, he carried him to Babylon, where he kepthim in the House of Discipline till the day of his death.
